A man firing several dozen shots from an automatic rifle killed six children and wounded 
35 at an elementary school in Stockton, California on Tuesday. He then shot himself in 
the head. Deputy Police Chief Ralph Tribble said that he is in custody. Eight of those shot 
were being treated at St. Joseph's Medical Center and at least 30 people were sent to 
other area hospitals, according to Police Chief Jack Calkins. The attack at Cleveland 
Elementary School came shortly before noon. Police received a call that a man went 
berserk with an automatic weapon and several people were down.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d095"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890117-0004"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="H">

On Tuesday, within hours after a gunman opened fire at Cleveland Elementary School in 
Stockton, CA, killing five children and himself and wounding 30 others, 25 translators 
who spoke Southeast Asian languages rushed to the school and hospitals to assist non-
English-speaking parents. One hospital called for help because its staff with language 
skills was overloaded. Translators were located and sent by the Charterhouse Center 
refugee program, which is funded by the Episcopal Church and private donations. 
Southeast Asians have been drawn recently by Stockton's farming and fishing. Sixty 
percent of the school's students are from Cambodia, Laos or Thailand. The five children 
killed were all Asian.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d095"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890118-0013"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="H">

Patrick E. Purdy, also known as Patrick West, was a blond, blue-eyed, 26-year-old drifter 
with a long criminal record in the LA area. He lived with an aunt and uncle in Sandy, 
Oregon, from July to October, then traveled to Texas, Tennessee, Connecticut, and 
finally Lodi, California, near his hometown of Stockton, looking for work. On Tuesday 
he opened fire on Cleveland Elementary School in Stockton, killing five children and 
wounding 29 others and a teacher, before taking his own life. His aunt and grandmother 
described him as a nice young man but a loner and childhood alcoholic. His father died 
years ago after being struck by a car.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d095"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA011889-0131"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="H">

Yesterday in Stockton, California, Patrick Edward Purdy turned an assault rifle on a 
crowded playground at Cleveland Elementary where he had been a student, killing five 
children and wounding 29 before killing himself. Most of the student body are children of 
Southeast Asian refugees. The quarter who came to school today were escorted past 
reporters. Flowers and an anti-racism banner adorned the entrance. Counselors assisted 
children in each classroom. Each child was given a stuffed animal at the principal's 
office. Purdy, a troubled loner with a history of alcoholism and brushes with the law, had 
wandered America looking for welding work. Toy soldiers were found in his Lodi motel 
room.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d095"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890118-0051"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="H">

Midday on Tuesday, 26-year old drifter Patrick Edward Purdy set his car on fire then 
entered the grounds of Cleveland Elementary School, where he fired 60 rounds before 
killing himself.  He was armed with an AK-47 assault rifle and two handguns, one with 
the word "victory" on its handle. Students inside got under their desks and sixth-graders 
all cried. Neighbors were shocked by violence in their quiet town. The city has been 
changing with the arrival of Southeast Asian refugees. Buddhist priests in sandals and 
robes were among the clergy called to console families. 60% of the school's students are 
of Southeast Asian descent, including the slain children.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d095"
TYPE="PERDOC"
