DOCREF="AP890118-0094"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="H">

A 26-year-old drifter with a long criminal record opened fire with an assault rifle at 
Cleveland Elementary School in Stockton, California Tuesday, killing five children and 
wounding 30 others before killing himself. Children and officials there will receive cards 
and encouragement from their counterparts at Oakland Elementary School in Greenwood, 
South Carolina, where a similar thing happened last September 26th. In Greenwood, a 
man with a history of mental problems opened fire with a handgun and killed two 
children and wounded nine. Physical education teacher Kat Finkbeiner, whose jaw was 
shattered in the shooting, helped subdue 19-year-old gunman Jamie Wilson. The 
California tragedy brought Greenwood painful memories.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d095"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890119-0221"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="H">

Patrick Edward Purdy, AKA Eddie Purdy West, 24, had blue eyes and blond hair. 
Through third grade he attended Cleveland Elementary School in Stockton, California, 
where he killed five children on Tuesday. His mother, divorced and remarried, took him 
and moved away. His father was killed by a car in 1981. Purdy dropped out of high 
school, took welding classes, then drifted around the country searching for work. In the 
LA area he was arrested on prostitution, marijuana, and weapons charges, and for robbery 
and receiving stolen property. He attempted suicide in jail. He had white supremacist 
leanings and was described as dangerous and mildly retarded.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d095"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA012189-0073"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="H">

A memorial ceremony will be held Monday at Stockton's Civic Auditorium for the five 
children gunned down Tuesday at Cleveland Elementary School by Patrick Edward 
Purdy, who then killed himself. Californians will observe five minutes of silence. 
Fourteen of the 30 injured remain in hospitals. Victims' families are receiving financial 
aid from the county victim/witness assistance program. Buddhist monks led prayers 
Friday as part of 3-day mourning ceremonies at the homes of Cambodian families who 
lost children. One father attended from Ohio after learning of his son's death on TV. His 
wife claims she thought he was dead. Governor Deukmejian is considering a ban on 
assault weapon sales.</SUM>

